  "success": true,
  "output": "## Findings\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper (no React/frontend — `output/*.html` are static CV templates, not app UI, so \"re-renders\" doesn't apply here). It runs every 12h across **114 configured sources** (`sources.yaml`), several of which paginate up to 400+ postings each, so the issues below scale with real volume, not just theory.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-73` (highest impact)\n\n`Store.diff()` does one `SELECT` **and** one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` per job, in a Python loop, against SQLite:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nFor a run fetching a few thousand jobs across 114 sources, that's 2N+ separate statement round-trips. Fix: load all existing hashes in one query, diff in Python, then batch-write:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n    new, changed, seen_keys = [], [], set()\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        seen_keys.add(job.key)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    if new:\n        cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,...,:now,:now)\",\n                         [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    if changed:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\",\n                         [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    unchanged_keys = seen_keys - {j.key for j in new} - {j.key for j in changed}\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nTurns O(N) round-trips into O(1) read + 3 batched `executemany` calls.\n\n### 2. Redundant regex compilation — `filters.py:11-12, 22-26` (highest impact)\n\n`_compile()` recompiles every include/exclude pattern **from scratch on every job**, inside `match()`, which runs once per job in the `filter_jobs` list comprehension:\n\n```python\ndef _compile(words): return [re.compile(...) for w in words if w]   # called per-job!\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n```\n\nWith, say, 20 keywords across include/exclude and a few thousand fetched jobs, that's tens of thousands of needless `re.compile()` calls. Fix: compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):   # pre-compiled\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n`re.compile` result caching (Python caches ~512 patterns internally) softens this somewhat, but you're still paying dict-lookup + list-rebuild overhead per job for no reason, and it silently falls off a cliff once the internal cache is evicted by other regex use elsewhere in the process (e.g. `agent.py`'s `_ATS_RULES`, Meta's token regexes).\n\n### 3. Dead memory retention — `Job.raw` (`models.py:52`, all fetchers)\n\nEvery parser stashes the **entire raw ATS payload** on `raw=j`, but `grep -rn \"\\.raw\"` across the codebase shows it's never read anywhere — `to_row()` even explicitly drops it before persisting (`store.py` via `d.pop(\"raw\", None)`). For big boards (Microsoft/Amazon/Netflix, up to 400 roles/run each), you're holding thousands of full JSON objects in memory for the entire pipeline run purely to throw them away. Either drop the field entirely, or make it explicitly opt-in/trimmed:\n\n```python\n# fetchers.py — parse_greenhouse etc.\nout.append(Job(..., raw=j))   # <- delete this kwarg everywhere, or\n```\n```python\n# models.py\nraw: dict[str, Any] = field(default_factory=dict, repr=False)   # <- remove field\n```\nSame applies to `title`, `location` etc. being duplicated in `raw` — it's the one field with unbounded, unused size.\n\n### 4. No HTTP caching for repeated fetches (`fetchers.py`)\n\nEvery 12h run does a **full re-fetch** of every board from page 1, even though most postings are unchanged between runs (that's the whole premise of the dedup store). Several ATS's (Greenhouse, Lever, Ashby) support `ETag`/`If-Modified-Since`. Since `store.py` already has a generic `meta` key/value table (used for the scan marker), it's a natural place to persist a per-source `ETag`:\n\n```python\nasync def _get_json(client, url, *, cache_key=None, store=None, **kw):\n    headers = kw.pop(\"headers\", {})\n    etag = store.get_meta(f\"etag:{cache_key}\") if store else None\n    if etag:\n        headers[\"If-None-Match\"] = etag\n    r = await _request(client, url, headers=headers, **kw)\n    if r.status_code == 304:\n        return None  # caller keeps last-known-good jobs, skips reparse\n    if store and (new_etag := r.headers.get(\"ETag\")):\n        store.set_meta(f\"etag:{cache_key}\", new_etag)\n    return r.json()\n```\nEven without conditional requests, this would cut bandwidth and rate-limit exposure across 114 sources significantly. Lower priority than #1/#2 since it requires threading `Store` into `fetch_all`, but worth doing given the scheduled 12h cadence.\n\n### 5. Redundant hashing — `models.py:66-69`, `store.py:88-97`\n\n`content_hash` (a SHA-256 over 4 fields) is a plain `@property`, recomputed on every access. In `diff()`, a **changed** job hits it twice: once in the comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`), then again inside `_update` → `to_row()` → `asdict(self)` + `self.content_hash`. Cheap per-call, but doubled across every changed job every run for no reason. Simplest fix: compute once per job and pass it through:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs):\n    ...\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = job.content_hash          # compute once\n        row = ...\n        if row is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now, h)\n        elif row[\"content_hash\"] != h:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now, h)\n```\n(`_insert`/`_update` take the precomputed hash instead of recalling `to_row()`'s internal call.) Minor relative to #1/#2, but free to fix while you're already touching `diff()`.\n\n### React re-renders\nNot applicable — no React/frontend code exists in this repo (`output/*.html` are static CV artifacts generated once via `agent.py pdf-render`, not a running UI).\n\n### Memory leaks\nNo classic leaks found — `Store` and `httpx.AsyncClient` are consistently used via context managers/`finally` blocks and closed properly (`pipeline.py:42`, `fetchers.py:783-787`, `notify.py`'s `smtplib.SMTP`). The only real memory concern is the unbounded `Job.raw` retention in #3 above, which is a footprint issue, not a leak.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order**: #1 (N+1 store writes) and #2 (regex recompilation) are the clear wins — both are pure waste that scales with job count and cost nothing to fix. #3 is a one-line deletion. #4 is the most valuable but requires more plumbing (worth a separate follow-up). #5 is minor cleanup, do it opportunistically with #1.\n",
